      "raw_response": "Looking at this problem, I need to find the MEX of {n\u22950, n\u22951, ..., n\u2295m}.\n\nThe set {n\u22950, n\u22951, ..., n\u2295m} = {n\u2295i : 0 \u2264 i \u2264 m}. The MEX is the smallest non-negative integer NOT in this set. A value v is in the set iff n\u2295v is in [0, m], i.e., n\u2295v \u2264 m. So MEX = smallest v such that n\u2295v > m.\n\nThe code tries to find the minimum value of n\u2295p for p \u2265 L where L = m+1. This is the correct reformulation. However, the algorithm is wrong.\n\nLet me trace through example 1: n=3, m=5, L=6. We need min(n\u2295p) for p\u22656.\n- p=6: 3\u22956=5, p=7: 3\u22957=4, p=8: 3\u22958=11, etc. Answer should be 4. Code gets min(best, 3\u22956=5) at the end, and checks candidates in the loop.\n\nThe greedy approach in the loop only considers cases where upper bits match L and one specific bit is flipped from 0\u21921. It misses many valid candidates and doesn't properly handle the constraint that p \u2265 L through a full bit-by-bit greedy search.\n\nFor example 3: n=3, m=2, L=3. Need min(n\u2295p) for p\u22653. p=3: 3\u22953=0. Code returns min(best, 0)=0. \u2713\n\nFor example 2: n=4, m=6, L=7. p=7: 4\u22957=3. Code returns 3. \u2713\n\nFor example 1: The loop at i=0, bit_L=0, prefix_L=6, p_candidate=6|1|0=7, n\u22957=4. best=4. Then n\u2295L=5. min(4,5)=4. \u2713\n\nBut consider a case where the optimal p requires setting a bit to 0 where L has 1 (compensated by a higher bit being set). The algorithm doesn't handle this. For instance, n=0, m=5, L=6 (binary 110). Min 0\u2295p for p\u22656 = 6. But optimal might be p=8\u21928. The loop: i=0, bit_L=0, p=110|1|0=111=7, 0\u22957=7. i=1, bit_L=1, skip. i=2, bit_L=1, skip. n\u2295L=6. Answer=6. Correct.\n\nBut try n=5 (101), m=9 (1001), L=10 (1010). Need min(5\u2295p) for p\u226510. p=10:5\u229510=15, p=11:14, p=12:9, p=13:8, p=14:11, p=15:10, p=16:21... So min is 8 at p=13.\n\nLoop: i=0, bit_L=0, prefix=1010, p=1010|1|0=1011=11, 5\u229511=14. i=1, bit_L=1, skip. i=2, bit_L=0, prefix=1000, p=1000|100|01=1101=13, 5\u229513=8. i=3, bit_L=1, skip. n\u2295L=5\u229510=15. best=8. \u2713\n\nLet me try n=1, m=0, L=1. Need min(1\u2295p) for p\u22651. p=1:0. Answer=0. Loop: i=0, bit_L=1, skip. n\u2295L=0. best=0. \u2713\n\nThe algorithm seems to work for these cases but I believe it can fail when the optimal p requires going above L by setting a higher bit than any bit in L. For large values this might not be covered. Actually, for bits above L's highest bit, bit_L=0, so those are checked. The candidate sets upper bits of L (all 0) and the target bit to 1, with lower bits matching n. This seems correct.\n\nAfter extensive testing, the algorithm appears to produce correct results. However, the approach is not rigorously proven and may fail on edge cases I haven't tested.\n\nWait - the code checks `if n > m: return 0`. But n > m doesn't guarantee MEX=0. For n=3, m=2: 3>2, returns 0. Correct since 0=3\u22953 but 3>m so 0 not in set. Actually n\u22950=3 which is >2, so 0 is not in the set, MEX=0. \u2713 But n=4, m=3: 4>3, returns 0. Set={4,5,6,7}, MEX=0. \u2713 Actually if n>m, then n\u22950=n>m, so 0\u2209set, MEX=0. \u2713\n\n{\"verdict\": \"PASS\", \"bugs\": []}",
